<HTMLInputElementPattern>
<summary>
The <strong><c>pattern</c></strong> property of the <see cref="HTMLInputElement"/> interface represents a <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Guide/Regular_expressions">regular expression</see> a non-null <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/input">input</see> value should match. It reflects the <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/input">input</see> element's <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Attributes/pattern"><c>pattern</c></see> attribute.
</summary>
<remarks>
<para>The <c>pattern</c> property is valid for <c>text</c>, <c>search</c>, <c>url</c>, <c>tel</c>, <c>email</c>, and <c>password</c> types. It defines a regular expression that the input's <see cref="HTMLInputElement.Value"/> must match in order for the value to pass <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Constraint_validation">constraint validation</see>.</para><para>If a non-<c>null</c> value doesn&amp;apos;t conform to the constraints set by the <c>pattern</c> value, the <see cref="'ValidityState'"/> object's read-only <see cref="'ValidityState.PatternMismatch'"/> property will be true.</para>
<para>-<see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/input">input</see><br/>-<see cref="HTMLInputElement.Value"/><br/>-<see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/input#client-side_validation">Client-side validation</see><br/>-<see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/:valid">:valid</see> and <see href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/:invalid">:invalid</see> pseudo-classes<br/></para>
<para><seealso href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/HTMLInputElement/pattern"> <em>See also on MDN</em> </seealso></para>
</remarks>
<value>A string.</value>
</HTMLInputElementPattern>
